<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A list of DIE values.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This is a singly-linked list, but instead of reversing the order of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// insertion, we keep a pointer to the back of the list so we can push in</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// order.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// There are two main reasons to choose a linked list over a customized</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// vector-like data structure.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  1 For teardown efficiency, we want DIEs to be BumpPtrAllocated.  Using a</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///     linked list here makes this way easier to accomplish.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///  2 Carrying an extra pointer per \\a DIEValue isn&#39;t expensive.  45% of DIEs</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///     have 2 or fewer values, and 90% have 5 or fewer.  A vector would be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///     over-allocated by 50% on average anyway, the same cost as the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///     linked-list node.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievaluelist"><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">class </span><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievaluelist">DIEValueList</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690"><span class="doxyHighlight">  </span><span class="doxyHighlightKeyword">struct </span><span class="doxyHighlight">Node : <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/intrusivebacklistnode">IntrusiveBackListNode</a> &#123;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><span class="doxyHighlight">    <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/dievalue">DIEValue</a> V;</span></CodeLine>
